# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# form-runtime-in-form.form — the runtime in Form's own voice, the rest
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Companion to `form-engine.form`. That file took the recipe-evaluator
# meta-circular — one Form arm per RBasic verb. This file walks the
# remaining runtime layers — lexer, parser, frame/closure, builtin
# dispatch, registries, substrate write — and tries to write each in
# Form. Where Form has the surface, the code runs. Where the surface
# is missing, the gap is marked `# GAP:` with the smallest extension
# that would close it.
#
# Asymmetry is the signal. Each `# GAP:` is one breath away from a
# more symmetric body; none are accidents, all are namable.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Layer 1 — the lexer
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Python lexer walks a master regex, picks the longest-matching
# (kind, value) at each cursor. Form has list/dict literals, `set`
# mutation, recursion, and indexing. A char-by-char scanner is
# structurally expressible — *if* the char primitives exist.

# What a single-char classifier would look like in Form:

defn is_digit(c) = c >= "0" && c <= "9";
defn is_alpha(c) = (c >= "a" && c <= "z") || (c >= "A" && c <= "Z") || c == "_";
defn is_ws(c) = c == " " || c == "\t" || c == "\n" || c == "\r";

# GAP-L1: char literals don't exist as a distinct type. `"0"` is a
#         StringLit of length 1. The comparisons above assume string
#         ordering is char-wise lexicographic — which Python's `<`
#         provides for single-char strings, but Form has no test that
#         pins this contract. Smallest extension: `ord(c)` + `chr(n)`
#         builtins, or a documented "single-char strings compare by
#         codepoint" guarantee. Without one, lexer-in-Form is operating
#         on undocumented Python semantics leaking through.

# An integer-token scan would be:

defn scan_int(s, i) = do {
    let j = i;
    let n = len(s);
    while j < n && is_digit(s[j]) {
        set j = j + 1
    };
    {kind: "INT", value: int(substring(s, i, j)), next: j}
};

# GAP-L2: `substring(s, start, end)` is not a registered builtin. The
#         `s[i]` index returns a single-char string (PR #1686), but
#         there is no range-slice. Smallest extension: `substring(s,
#         start, end)` builtin, or `s[a..b]` syntax.

# Master scanner — emits a token list:

defn tokenize(s) = do {
    let tokens = [];
    let i = 0;
    let n = len(s);
    while i < n {
        let c = s[i];
        if is_ws(c) then set i = i + 1
        else if is_digit(c) then do {
            let tok = scan_int(s, i);
            set tokens = concat(tokens, [tok]);
            set i = tok.next
        }
        else if is_alpha(c) then do {
            # ... scan_ident, same shape
            set i = i + 1
        }
        # ... + 30 more single-/double-char operator branches
        else fail
    };
    tokens
};

# GAP-L3: the token-pattern *registry* (`form_lexer._TOKEN_PATTERNS`) is
#         a Python list mutated by `register_token_pattern`. From Form
#         there is no surface to read or extend that registry. Smallest
#         extension: builtins `token_patterns()` (read), `register_token(
#         kind, regex)` (write). Once those exist, the if/else cascade
#         above collapses to a registry-walk: for each pattern in
#         token_patterns() try-match, take longest.
#
# GAP-L4: even with the registry visible, the matcher needs *regex*.
#         Form has no regex primitive. Two paths: (a) add `match_regex(
#         pattern, s, i)` builtin; (b) replace regex sources with
#         structured matchers — each pattern carries a `Recipe` that
#         describes its shape (char-class star, literal-then-ident,
#         etc.) and the substrate already has match. (b) is the more
#         coherent move — regex was always the foreign shape sitting
#         inside the substrate's grammar.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Layer 2 — the parser
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Recursive descent through precedence levels. Each level is shaped
# `lhs := higher; while peek matches op-at-this-level: lhs = BinOp(op,
# lhs, parse_higher())`. Form has recursion, `set`, and dicts; the
# shape itself is fine.

# A single precedence level expressed in Form:

defn parse_add(tokens, i) = do {
    let result = parse_mul(tokens, i);
    let lhs = result.ast;
    set i = result.next;
    while i < len(tokens) && (tokens[i].kind == "PLUS" || tokens[i].kind == "MINUS") {
        let op = tokens[i].value;
        set i = i + 1;
        let rhs_result = parse_mul(tokens, i);
        set lhs = {tag: "BinOp", op: op, left: lhs, right: rhs_result.ast};
        set i = rhs_result.next
    };
    {ast: lhs, next: i}
};

# This *runs* in today's Form, given AST-as-dict-with-tag. So the
# shape is expressible. What it cannot do yet:

# GAP-P1: the operator registry (`form_operators._OPERATORS`) carries
#         precedence numbers per token kind. The hardcoded ladder above
#         (parse_or → parse_and → parse_compare → parse_add → parse_mul)
#         is what we want to derive from the registry, not duplicate.
#         Smallest extension: builtin `operators_at_precedence(n)` and
#         `max_precedence()`. Then one generic `parse_at_level(tokens,
#         i, level)` reads the registry and there is no ladder to
#         maintain in Form *or* in Python.
#
# GAP-P2: the primary-atom registry (`form_atoms._ATOM_HANDLERS`) maps
#         token kind → handler closure. To dispatch from Form,
#         `dispatch[tokens[i].kind](tokens, i)` would call the result of
#         a dict index. **Form's FnCall takes a name (string), not a
#         callable expression — `(f)(x)` is not a parse.** This is the
#         single largest hole for registry-style dispatch. Smallest
#         extension: allow `expr(args)` where expr evaluates to a
#         Closure (extend FnCall.name → FnCall.callee : AST). Already
#         half-present — closures are first-class values; only the
#         call site is name-only.
#
# GAP-P3: the keyword registry (`form_rules`) carries
#         `(pattern, template)` pairs. The pattern DSL (Sequence,
#         Capture, IdentCapture, Opt, Literal, RepeatedCapture) is
#         Python-class-shaped. From Form, those classes are not
#         constructible. Smallest extension: `pattern.sequence([...])`,
#         `pattern.capture("name")`, etc., as substrate-resident
#         constructors that return recipes the parser already consumes.
#         self_host.py already builds these from Python; a Form
#         surface would let new keywords be added without Python.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Layer 3 — the AST evaluator
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# `form-engine.form` Part 2 already covers the *recipe* evaluator
# (NodeID → value) for 15 RBasic categories. The *AST* evaluator
# (Python dataclass → value) is what Python's `execute()` does — the
# bridge between parse and recipe-intern.

# An AST-as-dict evaluator branch, in Form:

defn eval_ast(ast, frame) = match ast.tag {
    "IntLit" => ast.value,
    "BinOp" => apply_op(ast.op, eval_ast(ast.left, frame), eval_ast(ast.right, frame)),
    "Identifier" => frame_lookup(frame, ast.name),
    "Let" => frame_bind(frame, ast.name, eval_ast(ast.value, frame)),
    "IfExpr" => if eval_ast(ast.cond, frame)
                then eval_ast(ast.then_branch, frame)
                else (if ast.else_branch == null then null
                      else eval_ast(ast.else_branch, frame)),
    _ => fail
};

# This is the SHAPE that runs. Two real gaps once you try to ship it:

# GAP-E1: frames are Python `Frame` objects with parent-pointer chains
#         and `lookup` / `bindings` / `has` / `subject` slots. To
#         express a frame in Form, dicts work — but the *parent chain*
#         needs cycle-free walking that today's `frame.lookup(name)`
#         provides. Without `frame_lookup(frame, name)` as a builtin
#         (or `Frame` as a substrate-resident shape), Form code has
#         to re-implement scope walking on top of dict-with-parent-
#         field — works, but the Python Frame's nuance (subject
#         frames, state stacks, exception handlers, delegate chains)
#         doesn't lift.
#
# GAP-E2: many AST tags (FnDef, FnCall, ForExpr, WhileExpr, DictExpr,
#         IndexExpr, TernaryExpr, MethodInvokeExpr, Access, MethodCall,
#         TryCatchExpr, OnChangeExpr, RaiseExpr, ResumeExpr,
#         DelegateExpr, UndoExpr, InverseExpr, CommonExpr,
#         MethodDefExpr, ProjectExpr, SaveExpr, RestoreExpr,
#         DiscardExpr, ChooseExpr, FailExpr, StopExpr, SelfRef,
#         WithExpr, MatchArm, MatchExpr, DoBlock) are roughly **31 AST
#         classes** in form.py. `form-engine.form` Part 2 has arms for
#         15 RBasic categories; the rest of the AST shapes don't all
#         have Recipe-category counterparts. Smallest extension: every
#         AST class needs a Recipe category so `n.category` from Form
#         can recognize it. Several already exist (RBlock.LET / DO /
#         SEQUENCE, RException.RAISE, RTry, RChoice, ...). The audit
#         is mechanical: enumerate the 31 classes, map each to its
#         RBasic NodeID, name the missing ones.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Layer 4 — registries (the meta-circular hinge)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Five registries live as Python module globals:
#
#   form_lexer._TOKEN_PATTERNS    — ordered list of (kind, regex)
#   form_atoms._ATOM_HANDLERS     — dict token-kind → closure
#   form_rules.<keyword registry> — dict name → (pattern, template)
#   form_operators._OPERATORS     — dict symbol → OperatorRule
#   form_eval._BINARY_EVAL, _UNARY_EVAL — dict op-symbol → category-NodeID
#
# From Form, none of these are visible as values, mutable as state, or
# iterable as collections. Today's `bootstrap_self_host()` calls Python
# `register_*` functions from Python. The substrate is read-only from
# Form (`/api/substrate/*` is REST read-only by design).

# What the surface would look like in Form if it existed:

# read:
let kinds = token_pattern_kinds();           # ["WS", "COMMENT", "PROJECT", ...]
let handler = atom_handler("INT");           # the closure that parses int literals

# write:
register_token_pattern("MY_OP", "\\$\\$");
register_atom("INT", fn(parser) = ...);

# GAP-R1: no Form surface for any of the five registries. Smallest
#         extension: builtins `token_pattern_kinds()`,
#         `token_pattern_regex(kind)`, `register_token_pattern(kind,
#         regex)`, parallel sets for atoms / keywords / operators /
#         eval-categories. Each registry is a few lines of Python
#         glue.
#
# GAP-R2: registry *values* are closures (atom handlers, operator
#         templates). Storing a Form-defined closure into a registry
#         requires Form closures to be passable to Python registration
#         functions and re-invokable when the parser reaches them.
#         Today, builtins pass closures through `_CURRENT_SESSION` to
#         re-enter `execute()`. The mechanism exists; the surface is
#         what's missing.
#
# GAP-R3: persistence. Registries are process-global. A Form module
#         that registers a keyword survives the current process, not
#         a fresh `coh substrate form` invocation. For "the body
#         remembers its own grammar", registrations must round-trip
#         through the substrate itself — each registered keyword
#         interned as a cell whose CTOR carries (name, pattern,
#         template). Today the patterns *are* substrate-resident
#         recipes; what's missing is the registry-as-substrate-table
#         that the parser reads at startup.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Layer 5 — substrate write
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Form reads the substrate (n.category, n.children[k], n.value).
# Form *cannot write* — there is no `intern_recipe(category, [children])`
# or `define_cell(domain, name, blueprint, recipe)` builtin.
#
# A self-hosted compiler — Form text → Recipe NodeID — needs write
# access. Today the compile path runs in Python (`_to_recipe_node_id`
# in form.py).

let plus_two_three = intern_recipe(
    @1.2.12.1,            # RBasic.MATH.PLUS
    [intern_trivial(2), intern_trivial(3)]
);

# GAP-W1: `intern_recipe(category, children)` not exposed as builtin.
# GAP-W2: `intern_trivial(value)` not exposed as builtin (the inverse
#         of `n.value` — encode a Python value as a trivial NodeID).
# GAP-W3: `define_cell(domain, name, blueprint_nid, recipe_nid)` not
#         exposed — the ingest path is Python-only.
#
# The REST surface is read-only by design (Tom's principle: writes are
# operational, reads are exploratory). But internal-to-Form should be
# different — the body should be able to recompose itself. Smallest
# extension: the three builtins above, with the same write paths the
# Python ingest functions use. Side-effect isolation can be done by
# scoping writes to a session-local recipe buffer that commits at
# block end (matching SAVE/RESTORE/DISCARD semantics already in BML).

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Summary — the asymmetry made specific
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Each gap below is a single extension. None is structural; all are
# surface. The body knows how to do every one of these in Python —
# it just doesn't yet have the Form-side word for it.
#
# Lexer (5):
#   L1  char primitives — ord/chr or codepoint-comparison contract
#   L2  substring(s, start, end) builtin
#   L3  token-pattern registry surface (read + register from Form)
#   L4  regex builtin OR structured matcher recipes (regex is foreign)
#
# Parser (3):
#   P1  operators_at_precedence(n) / max_precedence() — derive ladder
#   P2  callable expression at call site (FnCall.name → .callee : AST)
#       — single biggest hole; registry-style dispatch needs this
#   P3  pattern-DSL constructors as substrate-resident Form surface
#
# Evaluator (2):
#   E1  Frame as substrate-resident shape OR frame_lookup builtin —
#       so scope walking lifts with all its nuance (subject, state,
#       exceptions, delegate, common)
#   E2  Recipe category for each of the 31 AST classes (audit) —
#       extend form-engine.form Part 2 to symmetric coverage
#
# Registries (3):
#   R1  five registries (lexer / atoms / keywords / operators / eval)
#       each gain `list_*` + `register_*` Form-side builtins
#   R2  Form-defined closures register-able as handlers
#   R3  registries persist through substrate cells, not process state
#
# Substrate write (3):
#   W1  intern_recipe(category, children)
#   W2  intern_trivial(value)
#   W3  define_cell(domain, name, blueprint, recipe)
#
# That is 15 named gaps closing what Part 4 of form-engine.form
# pointed at (4a identifier resolution → E1; 4b call from recipes →
# P2 + E2; 4c lexer/parser in Form → L1-L4 + P1-P3 + R1-R3). Each
# names exactly one builtin or one constructor; none of them ask for
# a structural rebuild.
#
# The composition discipline holds: every gap is a *leaf surface*,
# not a re-shaping of the tree. The tree's already right.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# What's beneath the gaps — the kernel
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# "Everything else can be written in Form" implies a floor. Two
# vertical-slice kernels in `experiments/form-kernel-go/` (854 LoC)
# and `experiments/form-kernel-rust/` (737 LoC) carry the floor end-
# to-end — NodeID + content-addressed intern + recipe walker (22
# RBasic arms) + frame/closure system + native primitives (strings,
# lists, file I/O) + S-expression bootstrap reader. Both read `.fk`
# source files from disk and walk them. Five sample programs (fact,
# fib, closure, list-sum, string-walk) produce identical results in
# both kernels.
#
# Runtime comparison + honest read on language alignment lives in
# `experiments/form-kernel-comparison.md`. After three focused
# optimization breaths each (slice returns, interned NameIDs, arena
# frames + recipe-fold), both kernels stay under 1000 lines and
# produce identical results across every sample. Go ends up
# ~20-25% faster than Rust on long workloads; Rust's safety model
# carries a measurable runtime cost even with the Rc/RefCell tax
# eliminated. The trade lives between raw throughput (Go) and
# compiler-enforced structural discipline (Rust).
#
# What's still ahead, in breaths:
#   • The Form-surface-syntax parser written in Form itself (loaded
#     by the S-expression bootstrap reader, then takes over).
#   • The query layer in Form (?equivalent, |>, ?cells).
#   • Substrate persistence integration (cells round-trip through
#     Postgres / Neo4j from inside the kernel).
#   • Embedding the chosen kernel back into the existing Python API
#     surface (PyO3 for Rust, cgo for Go).
